                                 phrases, or difficult words).\n     a spoken response by an English                                            * Include some mid-clause\n     learner.                                                                   disfluencies, not only at sentence\n     Speaker profile:                                                           boundaries.\n     * Proficiency level (CEFR): [CEFR                                          * Do NOT overuse any single type.\n     LEVEL]                                                                     * Model disfluencies according to\n     Input text: [WRITTEN RESPONSE]                                             CEFR level.\n     ---                                                                        * Model hesitation frequency\n     Core constraints:                                                          according to CEFR level,\n     * Keep the original meaning exactly                                        distributing them naturally\n     the same.                                                                  across the text (not clustered or\n     * DO NOT correct grammar mistakes                                          periodic).\n     or improve the language.                                                   ---\n     * Preserve all learner errors.                                             Cognitive/production effects:\n     * Do NOT introduce new factual                                             Simulate real speaking behaviour:\n     content.                                                                   * Include signs of uncertainty or\n     ---                                                                        memory limits (e.g., ‘‘I think’’,\n     Goal:                                                                      ‘‘I don’t remember’’, ‘‘something\n     Produce a realistic transcription                                          like that’’) when appropriate.\n     of spontaneous speech, as if                                               * Allow vague references (e.g.,\n     the learner is speaking and                                                ‘‘that thing’’, ‘‘that kind of\n\fthings’’).\n* Do not make the speaker sound\nperfectly confident or precise.\n* Avoid perfectly structured\nsummaries.\n---\nProficiency adaptation:\n* Lower CEFR (A1{A2): shorter\nchunks, more hesitations, more\nrepetitions, simpler structure.\n* Mid CEFR (B1{B2): moderate\ndisfluency, some repairs, longer\nsentences.\n* High CEFR (C1{C2): mostly fluent,\noccasional hesitation for planning.\n---\nFormatting:\n* Keep punctuation clear and\nreadable.\n* Use commas, dashes, and ellipses\nto reflect pauses and repairs.\n* Do NOT produce raw ASR-style\ntext.\n* Output should remain compatible\nwith standard written text\nprocessing.\n---\nFinal requirement:\nThe output must resemble a real\nlearner transcript, capturing\nboth linguistic errors and the\ncognitive process of speaking, not\njust adding superficial noise. Only\noutput the trancript without adding\nany other comments or observations.\n\f", "numLines": 552, "startLine": 1, "totalLines": 552}}}
